wt4a366ba20a6c6_0.jpg&#39;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Anders Ross provides a definition, brief history, and best practices for designing infographics followed by a huge number of example screenshots. &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.instantshift.com/2009/06/07/infographic-designs-overview-examples-and-best-practices/&#34;&gt;View them all at Infoshift&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://www.instantshift.com/2009/06/07/infographic-designs-overview-examples-and-best-practices/&#34;&gt;http://www.instantshift.com/2009/06/07/infographic-designs-overview-examples-and-best-practices/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;notebook-screenshot&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://core77.com/blog/book_reviews/book_review_sketchbook_conceptual_drawings_from_the_worlds_most_influential_designers_by_timothy_odonnell_13737.asp&#34;&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://media.konigi.com/notebook/sketchbook-review.jpg&#34; class=&#34;notebook-image&#34; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Core77 reviews Timothy O&amp;rsquo;Donnell&amp;rsquo;s &lt;em&gt;Sketchbook&lt;/em&gt;, which looks at the problem solving processes of influential designers on finished projects through the lens of their sketchbooks. It looks beautiful. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;blockquoute&gt;Organized in three sections, &amp;ldquo;Rough,&amp;rdquo; &amp;ldquo;Refined,&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Random&amp;rdquo; (plus bonus section &amp;ldquo;Revealed,&amp;rdquo; where O&amp;rsquo;Donnell shows the thumbnail sketches he used to lay out the book), almost all sketches/sketchbook pages are pared with pictures of the finished product side by side. The &amp;ldquo;Rough&amp;rdquo; section features loose artwork and thick lines, but crisp final products, like the way Jason Munn turns simple sketches into iconic music posters, while the &amp;ldquo;Refined&amp;rdquo; section sees Stefan Bucher&amp;rsquo;s gorgeous pens turned into, well, equally iconic logos and business cards. Beyond nearly academic distinctions about the roughness of lines, the &amp;ldquo;Rough&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Refined&amp;rdquo; sections are nearly indistinguishable. Once again, it seems that the graphic designers capable of hand drawing typography consistently generate the prettiest sketchbooks. Chris Bigg&amp;rsquo;s felt pen album covers fill the stark pages with high contrast imagery and Rob O&amp;rsquo;Connor&amp;rsquo;s album covers are nearly as stimulating in ideation as they are as finished products. Perhaps it&amp;rsquo;s no surprise that graphic designers produce the prettiest sketchbooks, but it the tight confines of typography often generate the quickest and most inspirational sketches as well.&lt;/blockquoute&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Sketchbook&lt;/em&gt; &lt;a href=&#34;http://www.amazon.com/Sketchbook-Conceptual-Drawings-Influential-Designers/dp/1592535216?/tag=core77-20&#34;&gt;may be purchased at Amazon&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

