&lt;p&gt;&lt;div class=&#34;notebook-screenshot&#34;&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://jounce.net/blog/2009/jan/28/when-sitemaps-dont-work-two-alternatives/&#34;&gt;&lt;img id=&#39;bluga-thumbnail-1497&#39; class=&#39;bluga-thumbnail large&#39; src=&#39;http://media.konigi.com/bluga/
wt49999b9d531cb.jpg&#39;/&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Interesting discussion in M. Jackson Wilkinson&amp;rsquo;s blog about the &lt;a href=&#34;http://jounce.net/blog/2009/jan/28/when-sitemaps-dont-work-two-alternatives/&#34;&gt;altnernatives to hierarchical sitemaps&lt;/a&gt;, and the use of concept maps or user flows as alternatives when hierarchy doesn&amp;rsquo;t work in your documentation. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I have to agree with one point, in that site maps don&amp;rsquo;t always serve documentation well when the notion of a strict hierarchy just doesn&amp;rsquo;t exist. But I think there&amp;rsquo;s utility in sitemaps at conveying the organization of a site or application at some level. It may be a very high level visualization that maps concept model/mental models to navigation or application menus, and provides a way for a team to visualize the connections between what the user sees and what the system represents in UI. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I don&amp;rsquo;t do sitemaps very often anymore, especially when working on application design. They get you far enough in terms of conveying a 1,000 foot view of the landscape, but the meat of the documentation seems to be in uncovering topography. And that can be the stuff of quite a few deliverable types, including user flows, use cases. A nice list of deliverables that might be suitable is in Peter Morvilles&amp;rsquo; &lt;a href=&#34;user-experience-deliverables.html&#34;&gt;UX Deliverables run down&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://jounce.net/blog/2009/jan/28/when-sitemaps-dont-work-two-alternatives/&#34;&gt;http://jounce.net/blog/2009/jan/28/when-sitemaps-dont-work-two-alternatives/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

